VALUES
(44, 12, 19, 11, 20, 43, 43, NULL, 'Kings'' Displeasure and Consequences', 'This connection highlights the theme of royal displeasure leading to dire consequences. In both passages, the actions of the kings result in significant fallout, reflecting their emotional states and decisions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 19, 17, 6, 12, 12, NULL, 'Consequences of Actions', 'This connection highlights the theme of punishment following failure. In both passages, characters face dire consequences due to their actions, reflecting a moral order in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 19, 27, 2, 11, 13, 'commanded that they should be put to death', 'Kings'' Decrees and Punishments', 'This connection highlights the theme of kings issuing decrees that lead to the punishment of individuals. Both Herod and the Babylonian king demonstrate anger and a swift response to perceived failures, resulting in death sentences for those involved. The parallel in their actions underscores the authority and consequences wielded by rulers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 20, 15, 3, 7, 7, 'Tyre and Sidon', 'Connection of Tyre and Sidon', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between Tyre, Sidon, and external rulers. Acts 12:20 mentions Tyre and Sidon seeking peace with Herod, while Ezra 3:7 highlights their involvement in providing resources for rebuilding efforts under Persian authority.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 20, 26, 27, 17, 17, 'desired peace; because their country was nourished', 'Trade and Economic Relations', 'This connection highlights the economic interdependence between regions. Both passages reference trade relationships, with Acts mentioning Tyre and Sidon seeking peace due to their reliance on the king''s country, while Ezekiel details Judah and Israel''s trading activities.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 20, 40, 11, 21, 22, 'Tyre and Sidon', 'Repentance and Judgment Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the cities of Tyre and Sidon in relation to judgment and repentance. Acts highlights their need for peace with Herod, while Matthew contrasts their potential repentance with the unrepentant cities of Chorazin and Bethsaida.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 20, 42, 14, 31, 32, 'desired peace', 'Desire for Peace in Leadership', 'This connection highlights the theme of seeking peace in leadership situations. Both passages emphasize the importance of negotiation and the desire for peace when faced with conflict.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 20, 42, 16, 8, 8, 'desired peace', 'Wisdom in Seeking Peace', 'This connection highlights the theme of seeking peace through wise actions. In Acts, the people of Tyre and Sidon seek peace with Herod, while in Luke, the unjust steward is commended for his wise dealings to secure his future.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 20, 1, 10, 15, 15, 'Sidon', 'Connection of Tyre, Sidon, and Canaan', 'This connection highlights the geographical and cultural significance of Sidon, mentioned in both passages. Acts references Tyre and Sidon, cities linked to Canaan, the progenitor of Sidon.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 20, 6, 19, 29, 29, 'Tyre', 'Connection between Tyre and Herod', 'This connection highlights the significance of Tyre in both passages. Acts 12:20 mentions Tyre''s relationship with Herod, while Joshua 19:29 identifies Tyre as a strong city, indicating its importance in the region.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 22, 44, 14, 10, 13, 'the voice of a god', 'Divine Recognition by People', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s reaction to miraculous events, attributing divine status to human figures. In Acts 12:22, the crowd declares a voice as that of a god, while in Acts 14:11, they proclaim Paul and Barnabas as gods in human form.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 22, 65, 1, 16, 16, NULL, 'Connection of Complaints and Praise', 'This connection highlights the theme of flattery and the dangers of speaking great swelling words. Both passages address the tendency of people to elevate others, either by proclaiming them as divine or by admiring them for personal gain.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 22, 66, 13, 4, 4, 'It is the voice of a god', 'Worship of Powerful Figures', 'This connection highlights the theme of people attributing divine status to powerful figures. In Acts, the crowd declares a voice as that of a god, while in Revelation, the beast is worshipped, suggesting a similar elevation of authority.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 22, 19, 12, 2, 2, NULL, 'Flattery and Deception', 'This connection highlights the theme of flattery and deception in both passages. In Acts 12:22, the people flatter Herod by attributing divine qualities to him, while Psalms 12:2 warns against those who speak with flattering lips.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 22, 27, 6, 7, 7, 'It is the voice of a god', 'Divine Recognition and Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of authority, with the people in Acts attributing divine status to a voice, while in Daniel, the king is elevated above all others. This connection highlights the theme of human leaders being perceived as divine figures.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 23, 19, 115, 1, 1, 'gave not God the glory', 'Glory Given to God', 'This connection highlights the importance of giving glory to God, as seen in both passages. Acts 12:23 illustrates the consequence of failing to give God glory, while Psalms 115:1 explicitly calls for glory to be directed to God''s name.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 23, 44, 10, 25, 26, 'gave not God the glory', 'Glory and Humility in Worship', 'This connection highlights the theme of giving glory to God versus human worship. In Acts 12:23, the consequence of not giving God glory is severe, while in Acts 10:25-26, Peter emphasizes that he is merely a man and should not be worshipped.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 23, 53, 2, 4, 4, 'gave not God the glory', 'Divine Judgment and Exaltation', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment against those who exalt themselves. In both passages, the consequences of failing to give God glory or opposing Him are emphasized.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 23, 44, 14, 14, 15, 'gave not God the glory', 'Divine Glory and Human Humility', 'This connection highlights the theme of giving glory to God. In Acts 12:23, failure to give God glory results in divine judgment, while Acts 14:14-15 emphasizes the apostles'' insistence on directing glory to the living God, rejecting human veneration.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 23, 9, 25, 38, 38, 'the Lord smote', 'Divine Judgment and Death', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of divine judgment resulting in death. In Acts, the angel of the Lord smote Herod for not giving God glory, while in 1 Samuel, the Lord smote Nabal, leading to his death.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 23, 27, 4, 30, 37, 'gave not God the glory', 'Divine Judgment and Humility', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of pride and the necessity of giving glory to God. In Acts, the angel of the Lord smote Herod for not giving God the glory, while in Daniel, Nebuchadnezzar is humbled until he acknowledges God''s sovereignty.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 23, 27, 5, 18, 24, 'gave not God the glory', 'Divine Judgment and Pride', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of pride and failing to glorify God. In Acts, Herod''s refusal to give God glory leads to his demise, while in Daniel, Belshazzar''s pride and lack of humility result in divine judgment.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 24, 44, 6, 7, 7, 'the word of God grew and multiplied', 'Growth of the Word of God', 'Both passages emphasize the growth of the word of God and its impact on the community. Acts 12:24 states that ''the word of God grew and multiplied,'' while Acts 6:7 notes that ''the word of God increased'' and disciples multiplied.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 24, 44, 19, 20, 20, 'the word of God grew', 'Growth of the Word of God', 'Both passages emphasize the growth of the word of God, highlighting its increasing influence and power. The phrases ''grew and multiplied'' and ''mightily grew'' suggest a theme of expansion and effectiveness in the spread of God''s message.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 24, 53, 3, 1, 1, 'the word of God grew', 'Growth of the Word', 'Both passages emphasize the growth and spread of the word of God. Acts highlights the multiplication of God''s word, while 2 Thessalonians requests prayer for its free course and glorification.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 24, 40, 16, 18, 18, 'the word of God grew', 'Growth of the Church', 'This connection highlights the growth of the church as indicated in both passages. Acts 12:24 speaks of the word of God growing, while Matthew 16:18 emphasizes the establishment and resilience of the church.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 24, 51, 1, 6, 6, 'the word of God grew', 'Growth of God''s Word', 'Both passages emphasize the growth and fruitfulness of the word of God. Acts 12:24 states that ''the word of God grew,'' while Colossians 1:6 speaks of it ''bringing forth fruit'' in believers.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 24, 20, 28, 28, 28, 'the word of God grew', 'Growth of the Righteous', 'Both passages emphasize the increase of the righteous in times of change. Acts 12:24 speaks of the growth of God''s word, while Proverbs 28:28 highlights the increase of the righteous when the wicked perish.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 24, 23, 41, 10, 13, NULL, 'Growth and Divine Support', 'This connection highlights the growth of God''s word in Acts and the assurance of God''s support in Isaiah. Both passages emphasize God''s active role in strengthening and upholding His people.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 25, 44, 12, 12, 12, 'John, whose surname was Mark', 'Connection of John Mark', 'Both passages emphasize John, whose surname was Mark, linking his identity in the early church. The mention of his mother, Mary, in Acts 12:12 provides context for his role alongside Barnabas and Saul in Acts 12:25.', 'keyword', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
